Center: US National Nuclear Data Center, Brookhaven, USA
title: Gamma Radiation from B10 Bombarded by Protons

x4freetext: Gamma Radiation from B10 Bombarded by Protons

x4codes.hlp: California Institute of Technology, Pasadena, CA, United States of America
California Institute of Technology, Pasadena, CA, United States of America

x4freetext: California Institute of Technology 3-MeV
electrostatic accelerator.
Protons were accelerated in an electrostatic
generator and analyzed in energy by either a 90
degree electrostatic or magnetic analyzer set to give
an energy resolution of 0.1-0.2 percent. The beam
striking the target was measured by means of a
current integrator having an accuracy of a few percent.
Two types of targets were used: one
consisted of a thin layer of (B10)2O3 evaporated in
vacuo on a tantalum backing; the other was a thin
boron layer prepared by cracking diborane on hot
tantalum. In both of these the boron was enriched to
about 95% B10. The number of B10 nuclei per cm2
in these targets was determined by comparing the
yield of the B10(p,alpha gamma)Be7 reaction from the
various targets with the yield from a target of
normal B203. The thickness of this target had
previously been measured from the apparent width of
the 163-keV resonance of B11(p,gamma)C12 from the
target thickness the number of boron nuclei per cm2
was then calculated by using the stopping cross
section of B203.
The scintillation spectrometer consisted of
an Nal(T1) crystal 1.5, inches long and 1.5, inches
in diameter mounted on a 5819 photomultiplier. Pulses
from the photomultiplier were amplified and then
analyzed in a single-channel pulse-height analyzer.
In all of these measurements the counter was
placed at 90 degree to the proton beam with the front
face of the crystal 0.75 inch from the target.
Background measurements were made at frequent
intervals by bombarding a clean tantalum target.

x4freetext: The gamma-ray yield at the resonance peak was
obtained by integrating under the differential pulse
height curve and dividing by the counter efficiency.
The cross section could then easily be calculated
from the known target thickness.

x4freetext: Relative measurements.
Relative measurements made with a single-channel
analyzer and normalized to the absolute data at 2.3
MeV. The yield of this gamma ray was measured as a
function of proton bombarding energy with the aid of
a single-channel pulse-height analyzer set to
straddle the photopeak.
Fig. 3, page 1004.

x4freetext: At the lower energies the cross sections
are estimated to have an accuracy of 50%;
however, above 1.5 MeV the uncertainties in the data
and their interpretation were such that the cross
sections are good to only a factor of two or so.
The resonance at 1.2 MeV: When one corrects the data
obtained here for the target thickness the resonance
peak is at 1.21 MeV.
